f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Vertex calculates funding rates hourly based on the difference between the perpetual futures price and the underlying BTC spot price index. The hybrid architecture uses an off-chain sequencer for rapid order matching while maintaining on-chain settlement and risk engine validation. Cross-margin by default means funding payments affect your entire portfolio balance rather than isolated position margins. Rate calculations incorporate Vertex's weighted spot price index and 8-hour TWAP smoothing to reduce manipulation risk."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","BTC","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BTC/USDT on Vertex represents the largest volume pair on the platform, providing the most liquid funding rate arbitrage opportunities within the Arbitrum ecosystem. The hourly funding frequency creates 24 daily settlement events, offering more granular arbitrage windows than 8-hour funding cycles on major CEXs. Vertex's low taker fees at 0.02% make it cost-effective for high-frequency funding rate strategies targeting small rate differentials."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BTC/USDT funding rates on Vertex typically range from -0.1% to +0.3% annually, with higher volatility during significant Bitcoin price movements. The hourly settlement creates more frequent but smaller funding payments compared to 8-hour cycles, leading to smoother rate distributions. During bull markets, Vertex often shows positive funding rates as long positions dominate, while bear markets see negative rates as shorts increase. The DEX nature means rates can deviate more from CEX benchmarks during periods of low liquidity or high gas fees on Arbitrum."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Vertex's position as an Arbitrum-based DEX creates regular arbitrage opportunities against major CEXs like Binance and OKX due to different user bases and liquidity patterns. The 0.02% taker fee advantage over most CEXs (typically 0.04-0.05%) provides additional edge for funding rate arbitrage strategies. Cross-margin mechanics mean traders can optimize capital efficiency by using existing portfolio positions as collateral for arbitrage trades. The hourly funding cycle allows for more precise hedging of funding rate exposure compared to 8-hour cycles elsewhere."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Vertex's sequencer centralization creates operational risk where off-chain components could fail, potentially affecting position management during critical funding periods. Lower brand recognition and concentrated Arbitrum ecosystem exposure means less diverse liquidity during market stress. Cross-margin by default increases liquidation risk as funding payments affect total portfolio health rather than isolated positions. Bridge risks exist when moving funds to/from Arbitrum, and gas fee spikes can impact the economics of smaller arbitrage positions."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does Vertex calculate BTC/USDT funding rates?","answer":"Vertex calculates and settles funding rates every hour for BTC/USDT perpetual futures. This creates 24 funding events per day, providing more frequent arbitrage opportunities compared to exchanges using 8-hour funding cycles."},{"question":"What makes Vertex funding rates different from CEX rates?","answer":"Vertex operates as a hybrid DEX on Arbitrum with different user demographics and liquidity patterns than centralized exchanges. The platform uses cross-margin by default and has lower taker fees at 0.02%, which can lead to funding rate deviations from major CEXs."},{"question":"Can I use isolated margin for BTC funding rate arbitrage on Vertex?","answer":"No, Vertex uses cross-margin by default for all positions. This means funding payments affect your entire portfolio balance and margin calculations, requiring careful risk management when running arbitrage strategies across multiple positions."},{"question":"What are the main risks of funding arbitrage on Vertex?","answer":"Key risks include sequencer centralization where off-chain components could fail, bridge risks when moving funds to Arbitrum, and cross-margin liquidation risk. Additionally, lower liquidity during market stress and gas fee volatility can impact arbitrage profitability."}]}]
